english:
  title: A Record of the Chrysanthemum Stream
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My colleague Park Jae-joong, who serves in the Ministry of War, has inscribed the name 'Chrysanthemum Stream' above his dwelling and asked me to write this record. I said to him:

    "The chrysanthemum is the recluse among flowers; the mountain stream is the solitude among waters. Seclusion dwells in solitude, and solitude dwells in seclusion—such is the kinship of their essence. Yet you and I have already shed our robes of youth and entered the Jade Hall of office, served in the Golden Departments. All that men of station covet and admire, you have received without hesitation. How then could you harbor a longing for reclusion?

    Your spirit is refined and luminous, your nature beautiful and clear. Such lofty aspirations, such elegant and graceful bearing—like pure gold and flawless jade, radiant as mountains, serene as seas. How could you draw near to solitude?

    And yet, since such are your choices, your heart's desires cannot be questioned. For the benevolent love mountains, and the wise love water—such is the calling of virtue. What Jae-joong has found in his heart must surely reside somewhere, and his dwelling must reflect this truth.

    You serve your parents with filial devotion, making their contentment your urgent task. Your office seeks to honor them, not yourself. You cultivate your character, making luminous virtue your work. Your words aim to reveal the Way, not to display yourself. This is filial piety alone—yet your spirit yearns for retreat. This is clarifying virtue alone—yet your heart seeks quietude. Clearly, neither fame nor riches can touch you.

    Should fortune one day grant you high station, elevated to the counselor's seat, commanding the army's strength—then your duty to nurture your parents would be fulfilled completely. How could such service compare to mere self-aggrandizement? And when you climb mountains and stand by waters, when things stir your feelings and ravines and mists call to your imagination, such longings cannot be hidden. It is fitting that you inscribe your dwelling thus.

    As for me—I approach the peony, yet dwell in stagnant pools. How can I not be ashamed before wealth and honor, much less before heaven's judgment? Gazing upon Chrysanthemum Stream, I am struck with shame.

    Yet this is true: heaven and earth share one breath; mountains, rivers, grass, and trees share one breath. How can we weigh them differently?

    Ah, this is what I would speak of with you, Jae-joong.

    Written in the fourth month of summer, in the year Kyeongsin.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Jade Hall' (옥당) refers to the Hongmungwan, the royal secretariat where elite scholars served.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Golden Departments' (금성) likely refers to other prestigious government ministries.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Chrysanthemum'' (국/菊) symbolizes loyalty and reclusion in East Asian poetry, while the stream (澗) represents solitude and purity.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to peony and stagnant pools is the author's self-deprecating way of acknowledging his own distance from such virtue and simplicity.
